        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down,</placeName>
                    <date>April 4, 1876.</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you for your very obliging letter and present of the essay and seeds.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I cannot but think that the principle on which you are acting is right, and if you succeed you will have conferred an enormous benefit on the public.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am sorry that I was compelled to decline my answer being published, for I cannot to the present hour remember what I said<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10437.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from James Torbitt, 1 April 1876</ref>. Torbitt sent his pamphlet on potato blight, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9032.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Torbitt 1876</ref>, which was accompanied by a packet of seeds. CD’s copy and the seeds have not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Torbitt proposed that growing potatoes from seed and collecting seeds from plants that resisted disease over successive generations was the best way to improve yields (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_9032.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Torbitt 1876</ref>, pp. 3–4).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10437.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from James Torbitt, 1 April 1876</ref> and n. 2. Torbitt wanted to publish CD’s reply to the question ‘what is an individual?’, contained in the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-10368.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to James Torbitt, 26 January 1876</ref>.</note>
